    pearls: ["Ionized calcium is the physiologically active form; always order it in critically ill patients, those with abnormal albumin, or acid-base disturbances","Magnesium must be repleted BEFORE calcium -- hypomagnesemia causes both PTH resistance and impaired PTH secretion, making hypocalcemia refractory to treatment","In primary hyperparathyroidism, calcium is HIGH and phosphorus is LOW (PTH drives renal phosphorus wasting); in CKD, both calcium and phosphorus handling are impaired","Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia (FHH) mimics primary hyperparathyroidism but has low urine calcium excretion and does NOT benefit from surgery -- differentiate with calcium-to-creatinine clearance ratio","Post-thyroidectomy: monitor for hypocalcemia every 6-8 hours for 48 hours; hungry bone syndrome can cause profound, prolonged hypocalcemia requiring IV calcium infusion","Granulomatous diseases (sarcoidosis) cause hypercalcemia via ectopic 1-alpha-hydroxylase in macrophages -- treat with corticosteroids, NOT with IV fluids and bisphosphonates alone"],
